paragraphs.text: %md ## Classification modeling to predict Target Customers using Support Vector Machine Model Oracle Machine Learning for R (OML4R) makes the open source R scripting language and environment ready for the enterprise and big data. Designed for problems involving both large and small data volumes, OML4R integrates R with Oracle Autonomous Database, allowing users to run R commands and scripts for statistical, machine learning, and visualization analyses on database tables and views using R syntax. Many familiar R functions are overloaded that translate R behavior into SQL for running in-database. In this notebook, we predict customers most likely to be positive responders to an Affinity Card loyalty program. High Affinity Card responders (target value = 1) are defined as those customers who, when given a loyalty or affinity card, hyper-respond, that is, increase purchases more than the Affinity Card program's offered discount. This notebook builds and applies a classification support vector machine model using the Sales History (SH) schema data. All processing occurs inside Oracle Autonomous Database. msg.data:
Classification modeling to predict Target Customers using Support Vector Machine Model

Oracle Machine Learning for R (OML4R) makes the open source R scripting language and environment ready for the enterprise and big data. Designed for problems involving both large and small data volumes, OML4R integrates R with Oracle Autonomous Database, allowing users to run R commands and scripts for statistical, machine learning, and visualization analyses on database tables and views using R syntax. Many familiar R functions are overloaded that translate R behavior into SQL for running in-database.

In this notebook, we predict customers most likely to be positive responders to an Affinity Card loyalty program.

High Affinity Card responders (target value = 1) are defined as those customers who, when given a loyalty or affinity card, hyper-respond, that is, increase purchases more than the Affinity Card program's offered discount.

This notebook builds and applies a classification support vector machine model using the Sales History (SH) schema data. All processing occurs inside Oracle Autonomous Database.

%r

DEMO_DF <- SUP_DEM[,c("CUST_ID", 'AFFINITY_CARD', "BOOKKEEPING_APPLICATION", "BULK_PACK_DISKETTES", "EDUCATION", "FLAT_PANEL_MONITOR", "HOME_THEATER_PACKAGE",

paragraphs.title: Create train and test data (60/40 split)
paragraphs.text:
%r

sampleSize <- .4 * nrow(DEMO_DF)
index <- sample(1:nrow(DEMO_DF),sampleSize)
group <- as.integer(1:nrow(DEMO_DF) %in% index)

paragraphs.title: Create train and test data sets
paragraphs.text:
%r

rownames(DEMO_DF) <- DEMO_DF$CUST_ID
DEMO_DF.train <- DEMO_DF[group==FALSE,]
class(DEMO_DF.train)
cat("\nTraining data: ")
dim(DEMO_DF.train)

DEMO_DF.test <- DEMO_DF[group==TRUE,]
class(DEMO_DF.test)
cat("\nTest data: ")
dim(DEMO_DF.test)

%md
## Build a Support Vector Machine Model for Predicting AFFINITY_CARD

msg.data: Build a Support Vector Machine Model for Predicting AFFINITY_CARD

paragraphs.title: Build a SVM Model using default settings
paragraphs.text:
%r

ore.exec("BEGIN DBMS_DATA_MINING.DROP_MODEL(model_name=> 'SVM_CLASSIFICATION_MODEL'); EXCEPTION WHEN others THEN null; END;")

MOD <- ore.odmSVM(AFFINITY_CARD~., DEMO_DF.train, "classification", kernel.function = "system.determined",odm.settings=list(model_name="SVM_CLASSIFICATION_MODEL"))    

RES <- predict(MOD, DEMO_DF.test, 
               type= c("raw","class"), norm.votes=TRUE, cache.model=TRUE, 
               supplemental.cols=c("CUST_ID", "AFFINITY_CARD", "EDUCATION", "HOUSEHOLD_SIZE", "OCCUPATION", "YRS_RESIDENCE"))

paragraphs.title: Confusion Matrix
paragraphs.text:
%r

CMATRIX <- with(RES, table(AFFINITY_CARD,PREDICTION))   
CMATRIX

paragraphs.title: Show model accuracy
paragraphs.text:
%r

ACCURACY <- CMATRIX/sum(CMATRIX)
round(sum(diag(ACCURACY)),3)

%md ### Examples of possible setting overrides for SVM If the user does not override the default settings, then relevant settings are determined by the algorithm A complete list of settings can be found in the Documentation link: -- Algorithm Settings: Support Vector Machine -- Shared Settings: All Algorithms -- Specify a row weight column 'ODMS_ROW_WEIGHT_COLUMN_NAME' = '' -- Specify a missing value treatment method. The default is to replace with mean (numeric features), mode (categorical features) or delete the row 'ODMS_MISSING_VALUE_TREATMENT' = 'ODMS_MISSING_VALUE_DELETE_ROW' -- Switch between Kernel Types - Linear or Gaussian By default the system uses the Linear Kernel. The linear kernel also is able to return the coefficients, while this is not available on the Gaussian 'SVMS_KERNEL_FUNCTION' = 'SVMS_LINEAR' 'SVMS_KERNEL_FUNCTION' = 'SVMS_GAUSSIAN' -- Value of complexity factor for SVM algorithm (both classification and regression). Default value estimated from the data by the algorithm. 'SVMS_COMPLEXITY_FACTOR' = '0.1' -- Type of regularization that the SGD SVM solver uses (only available for linear SVM models). The default is system determined because it depends on the potential model size. 'SVMS_REGULARIZER' = 'SVMS_REGULARIZER_L1' 'SVMS_REGULARIZER' = 'SVMS_REGULARIZER_L2' -- Specify a regularization setting for regression, similar to complexity factor. Epsilon specifies the allowable residuals, or noise, in the data. It takes a value larger than 0. The default is 0.1. 'SVMS_EPSILON' = '0.1' -- Batch rows sets the size of the batch for the SGD solver (linear kernel only). An input of 0 triggers a data driven batch size estimate. The default is 20000. 'SVMS_BATCH_ROWS' = '20000' -- Solver type, which cannot be selected if the kernel is non-linear. The default value is system determined. 'SVMS_SOLVER' = 'SVMS_SOLVER_SGD' 'SVMS_SOLVER' = 'SVMS_SOLVER_IPM' -- Specify the convergence tolerance for SVM algorithm. It requires a number larger than 0. Default is 0.0001. 'SVMS_CONV_TOLERANCE' = '0.001' -- Specify an upper limit on the number of pivots used in the Incomplete Cholesky decomposition. It can be set only for non-linear kernels. It requires a value from a range of 1 to 10,000 (inclusive of the edges). The default value is 200. 'SVMS_NUM_PIVOTS' = '200'

msg.data:
Examples of possible setting overrides for SVM

If the user does not override the default settings, then relevant settings are determined by the algorithm

A complete list of settings can be found in the Documentation link:

– Algorithm Settings: Support Vector Machine

– Shared Settings: All Algorithms

– Specify a row weight column

'ODMS_ROW_WEIGHT_COLUMN_NAME' = '<row_weight_column_name>'

– Specify a missing value treatment method. The default is to replace with mean (numeric features), mode (categorical features) or delete the row

'ODMS_MISSING_VALUE_TREATMENT' = 'ODMS_MISSING_VALUE_DELETE_ROW'

– Switch between Kernel Types - Linear or Gaussian
By default the system uses the Linear Kernel. The linear kernel also is able to return the coefficients, while this is not available on the Gaussian

'SVMS_KERNEL_FUNCTION' = 'SVMS_LINEAR'
'SVMS_KERNEL_FUNCTION' = 'SVMS_GAUSSIAN'

– Value of complexity factor for SVM algorithm (both classification and regression).
Default value estimated from the data by the algorithm.

'SVMS_COMPLEXITY_FACTOR' = '0.1'

– Type of regularization that the SGD SVM solver uses (only available for linear SVM models). The default is system determined because it depends on the potential model size.

'SVMS_REGULARIZER' = 'SVMS_REGULARIZER_L1'
'SVMS_REGULARIZER' = 'SVMS_REGULARIZER_L2'

– Specify a regularization setting for regression, similar to complexity factor. Epsilon specifies the allowable residuals, or noise, in the data. It takes a value larger than 0. The default is 0.1.

'SVMS_EPSILON' = '0.1'

– Batch rows sets the size of the batch for the SGD solver (linear kernel only). An input of 0 triggers a data driven batch size estimate. The default is 20000.

'SVMS_BATCH_ROWS' = '20000'

– Solver type, which cannot be selected if the kernel is non-linear. The default value is system determined.

'SVMS_SOLVER' = 'SVMS_SOLVER_SGD'
'SVMS_SOLVER' = 'SVMS_SOLVER_IPM'

– Specify the convergence tolerance for SVM algorithm. It requires a number larger than 0. Default is 0.0001.

'SVMS_CONV_TOLERANCE' = '0.001'

– Specify an upper limit on the number of pivots used in the Incomplete Cholesky decomposition. It can be set only for non-linear kernels. It requires a value from a range of 1 to 10,000 (inclusive of the edges). The default value is 200.

'SVMS_NUM_PIVOTS' = '200'

paragraphs.text:
%md
## Display ROC Curve, Lift Chart, and Distribution Chart

msg.data: Display ROC Curve, Lift Chart, and Distribution Chart

paragraphs.text:
%r

# BAR PLOT
res <- ore.pull(RES)
sensitivity <- res[order(res$"'1'",decreasing = TRUE), ]
sens <- sum(sensitivity$"'0'")/sum(sensitivity$"'0'") - cumsum(sensitivity$"'0'")/sum(sensitivity$"'0'")
spec <- cumsum(sensitivity$"'1'")/sum(sensitivity$"'1'")

# LIFT CHART
decile2 <- quantile(sensitivity$"'1'", probs = seq(.1, .9, by = .1))
df_sens <- as.data.frame(sensitivity$"'1'", col.names = c("sens"))
df_sens$decile = as.numeric(cut(1-cumsum(df_sens$sens), breaks=10))


# DISTRIBUTION CHART
dx <- density(res$"'0'")
dx2 <- density(res$"'1'")

# PLOTS 3x1
par(mfrow=c(3,3))
plot(1 - spec, sens, type = "l", col = "darkred", ylab = "Sensitivity", xlab = "1 - Specificity", main = 'ROC Curve')
abline(c(0,0),c(1,1))
paste("AUC: ", round(sum(spec*diff(c(0, 1 - sens))),3)) 

barplot(table(df_sens$decile), xlab = 'Decile', ylab = 'Actual Targets', main = 'Lift Chart', col = "darkred")

plot(dx, lwd = 2, col = "burlywood",
     main = "Density")
lines(dx2, lwd = 2, col = "darkred")
# Add the data-poins with noise in the X-axis
rug(jitter(res$"'0'"),col='burlywood')
rug(jitter(res$"'1'"),col='darkred')

%md

### Use SQL interface for prediction details

paragraphs.title: Create table for use in SQL query
paragraphs.text:
%r

ore.drop(table = "SVM_TEST_TABLE")
ore.create(DEMO_DF, table ="SVM_TEST_TABLE")

paragraphs.title: Demonstrate using the SQL interface so score data and display prediction details
paragraphs.text:
%sql

SELECT CUST_ID,
    round(PREDICTION_YRS_RES,3) PRED_YRS_RES,
    RTRIM(TRIM(SUBSTR(OUTPRED."Attribute1",17,100)),'rank="1"/>') FIRST_ATTRIBUTE,
    RTRIM(TRIM(SUBSTR(OUTPRED."Attribute2",17,100)),'rank="2"/>') SECOND_ATTRIBUTE,
    RTRIM(TRIM(SUBSTR(OUTPRED."Attribute3",17,100)),'rank="3"/>') THIRD_ATTRIBUTE
FROM (SELECT CUST_ID,
             PREDICTION(SVM_CLASSIFICATION_MODEL USING *) PREDICTION_YRS_RES,
             PREDICTION_DETAILS(SVM_CLASSIFICATION_MODEL USING *) PD
      FROM SVM_TEST_TABLE
      WHERE CUST_ID < 100015
      ORDER BY CUST_ID) OUT,
               XMLTABLE('/Details'
                        PASSING OUT.PD
                        COLUMNS 
                        "Attribute1" XMLType PATH 'Attribute[1]',
                        "Attribute2" XMLType PATH 'Attribute[2]',
                        "Attribute3" XMLType PATH 'Attribute[3]')  OUTPRED
